      <lg type="edition">
<l>urumicai muḻakkeṉa muraca micaippac</l>
<l>cerunavil vēḻaṅ koṇmū vākat</l>
<l>tērmā vaḻituḷi talaii nāmuṟak</l>
<l>kaṇaikkāṟ ṟeṭutta kaṇṇakaṉ pācaṟai</l>
<l>yiḻitaru kurutiyō ṭēntiya voḷvāṭ</l>
<l>piḻivatu pōlap piṭ<supplied>ṭai</supplied>yū <supplied>ṟu</supplied>vappa†</l>
<l>mainta rāṭiya mayaṅkuperun tāṉaik</l>
<l>koṅkupuṟam peṟṟa koṟṟa vēntē</l>
<l><gap quantity="22" reason="lost" unit="character"/>taṇṭa māppoṟi</l>
<l>maṭakkaṇ mayiliyaṉ maṟali yāṅku</l>
<l>neṭuñcuvar nallil pulampak kaṭaikaḻintu</l>
<l>meṉṟōṇ makaḷir maṉṟam pēṇār</l>
<l>puṇṇuva<gap quantity="44" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l><gap quantity="10" reason="lost" unit="character"/>yaṇiyap puravi vāḻkeṉac</l>
<l>coṉṉiḻa liṉmaiyi ṉaṉṉiḻaṟ cēra</l>
<l>nuṇpūṇ mārpiṟ puṉṟalaic ciṟāa</l>
<l>rampaḻi poḻutiṟ ṟamarmukaṅ kāṇā</l>
<l><gap quantity="19" reason="lost" unit="character"/>ṟ ṟokkāṉa</l>
<l>vēntupuṟaṅ koṭutta vīyntuku paṟantalai</l>
<l>māṭa mayaṅkeri maṇṭik kōṭiṟu</l>
<l>purumeṟi malaiyi ṉirunilañ cērac</l>
<l>ceṉṟōṉ maṉṟa coe<gap quantity="12" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l><gap quantity="11" reason="lost" unit="character"/>ṇṇaṟiṉar kaṇṭukaṇ ṇalaippa</l>
<l>vañci muṟṟam vayakkaḷa ṉāka</l>
<l>vañcā maṟava rāṭpōr paḻittuk</l>
<l>koṇṭaṉai peruma kuṭapulat tatari</l>
<l>polika vattainiṉ paṇaitaṉaṟa<gap quantity="4" reason="lost" unit="character"/>ḷam</l>
<l>viḷaṅkutiṇai vēntar kaḷantoṟuñ ceṉṟu</l>
<l>pukarmuka mukavai polikeṉ ṟēttik</l>
<l>koṇṭaṉa reṉpa periyōr yāṉu</l>
<l>maṅkaṇ mākkiṇai yatira voṟṟa</l>
<l><gap quantity="18" reason="lost" unit="character"/>le ṉāyiṉuṅ kātali ṉētti</l>
<l>niṉṉō raṉṉōr piṟariva ṇiṉmaiyiṉ</l>
<l>maṉṉeyiṉ mukavaikku vanticiṟ peruma</l>
<l>pakaivar pukaḻnta vāṇmai nakaivarkkut</l>
<l>tāviṉ ṟutavum paṇpiṟ pēyoṭu</l>
<l>kaṇanari tiritaru māṅka ṇiṇaṉaruntu</l>
<l>ceñcevi yeruvai kuḻīi</l>
<l>yañcuvaru kiṭakkaiya kaḷaṅkiḻa vōyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>With a war camp wide in area, where, (4cd)</l>
<l>while drums sound like thunder-sounding thunder, (1)</l>
<l>with fight-trained elephant bulls as clouds,</l>
<l>showering dwindling drops of chariot horses, fearfully, (3)</l>
<l>	the wind raises arrows, (4ab)</l>
<l>with a mixed(?) big army in which warriors dance, (7)</l>
<l>while [their] bright swords that they hold up with blood flowing down (5)</l>
<l>rejoice in obstacles ???, like squeezing [them] out, (6)</l>
<l>o victorious king who obtained the outside of the Koṅku land, (8)</l>
<l><gap quantity="15" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>thus fighting [their] natures of peacocks with large dots [and] innocent eyes (9d-10)</l>
<l>passing the gate so that the good hall with tall walls is lonely, (11)</l>
<l>women with soft shoulders won’t mind the village common, (12)</l>
<l>……… </l>
<l>in order to join the good shade, in the absence of the shade of words (15)</l>
<l>saying “may [your] decorated horses live”, (14)</l>
<l>ruddy-headed youngsters, fine ornaments on [their] chests, (16)</l>
<l>not seeing the faces of their people at the time arrows destroy [them], (17)</l>
<l>…….</l>
<l>in the wasteland, destroyed [and] wasted, on which the king had turned [his] back, (19)</l>
<l>thrusting confused flames at the mansions, tusks breaking, (20)</l>
<l>he who has gone indeed (22ab)</l>
<l>to join the dark ground like a mountain struck by thunder (21) </l>
<l>…………</l>
<l>While the eyes are harrassed, seeing, of those who know…, (23)</l>
<l>with Vañci as a strong vessel with a courtyard, (24)</l>
<l>destroying heaps of men, fearless warriors, (25)</l>
<l>you have taken, great man, the thrashing cattle of the western region. (26)</l>
<l>May your Paṇai drum flourish. … (27a-c)</l>
<l>Going to each battle field of kings with shining families, (28)</l>
<l>may those with spotted faces that were drawn by you flourish. – thus praising (29)</l>
<l>they have taken, they say, great people. While I too, (30=</l>
<l>beat [my] pretty-eyed Kiṇai drum so that it reverberates, (31a-c)</l>
<l>although ………………. praising with love (32)</l>
<l>in the absence here of any others who would be like your people, (33)</l>
<l>I have come to [your] royal fortress for the things you drew, great man, (34)</l>
<l>– you who are the lord of the battle field of expanses to which fear comes, (39)</l>
<l>as red-eared kites flock [there] (38)</l>
<l>eating fat in that place where jackals roam in hordes (37)</l>
<l>along with Pēy of quality who will help without fault, (36)</l>
<l>for those who smile at [your] manliness that is praised [even] by [your] enemies. (35)</l>
</lg>
